metadata.name: Trasiedoc #332
metadata.description:
Behind every generative art project is a code. This code is sometimes a masterpiece but most viewers do not see it.

With the Trasiedoc project I wanted to highlight the hidden face of generative art, the code, by literally integrating the code of my biggest project to date (Dencity) in each output of the Trasiedoc project.

Margins can be hidden by pressing "x" in live mode (and optionally press "p" to see if anything happens).

Made with ‚ù§Ô∏è, code, code and p5js.

metadata.name: Mina #36
metadata.description:
A generative series of a-symmetric compositions.

Mina is a search for new textures created by combining 3 colors with 3 different mathematical equations.

Observe how Mina blends and creates its textures in time.

Probabilities;

- 18 color palettes.

- 2 background colors.

- 4 line placements.

- 14 different compositions, most of them have variations.


Made with p5.js

Ilgƒ±n ƒ∞√ß√∂z√º, December 2021
@distcollective

metadata.name: Resorting #32
metadata.description:
The idea of living within close proximity to nature has enticed people for centuries, especially for the ones used to living in bustling cities. Just picturing a cozy resort in the countryside, or playing music that resembles the feelings of holiday-making can drive us to go on a well-deserved vacation. Even when we don‚Äôt know where to, or whether we have the time or resources to slip out of our busy days, or even if that destination exists only in our imaginations. But when we do entertain ourselves with such ideas, we feel like we have taken a step to heal ourselves or to give our mind a worthy time out.

On the other hand, we have been living in human-focused settlements like cities for around 10,000 years, and we have all we need in an urban landscape, yet the idea of living in a secluded resort close to nature kept inviting us. This begs the question: were we supposed to live adjacent to nature to live well? Is it in our nature that we are wired to go back to the world beyond our doors? Or was it because we are aware of how big nature is, and how little time and resources we have to explore them all?

------------
Press [s] to save captured image
------------
It may take a few seconds to render, depending on the device.

created using WEBGL on p5.js
dirbots - Dec22

metadata.name: d/e/m/boss invaders #178
metadata.description:
Invaders is an algorithm that builds rows of rectangles and plays with repetition, colors and depth order.
Outputs reminds me space invaders, but some looks like motherboard circuits, temples, or just a overhead map from a hotel room emergency exit

Please be patient, it takes a while to render (25-45 secs) and draws around 6M circles during 4 steps.

Responsive, zoom out browser window and refresh to get a larger output.
's' save the current canvas

Invaders is part of a series playing with textures creating emboss/deboss effect.

metadata.name: Ichigo #197
metadata.description:
This generator is named 'Ichigo' (Ëã∫/ „ÅÑ„Å°„Åî), the Japanese word for 'strawberry'. 

Seeing each iteration from a suitable distance, small dots (to me, reminiscent of strawberry seeds) overlay different sequences of geometric repetitions, implying a sense of texture, grittiness and irregularity. 

By looking closer however, it becomes apparent to the viewer that the majority of the composition is in fact government by orderly elements, in this case grids of dots. 

This discovery invites the viewer to consider the output in front of them at different levels, near and far. At what point do you feel the dots begin to dissolve into a texture? When do you stop noticing the dots and instead begin to perceive the overall composition?

These questions are posed in a similar fashion as with meditation; at what point does something become something else? When does an in-breath become an out-breath and vice versa? 

Contemplation on simple questions like these can open a small portal into stillness and mindfulness by taking time to slowly observe our responses. 

23 palettes are included, each named after different areas of Tokyo. 

Press 'S' to download a full size 6000px x 6000px PNG output. 

As always, much gratitude and enjoy your piece.

metadata.name: Sands of Time #282
metadata.description:
We've been recently inspired to do this work while being on vacation, in one the most vibrant cities in the world, in the hot pot and intermixture of cultures, terrains and soundscapes. Borrowing the metaphors of sand, from Negarestani's "Cyclonopedia", and of time from "Chronosis", these living substances, we wanted to represent some of the vibes, that have been implanted into our gritty enduring nomadic existence.

This work was created to celebrate #fxhashturnsone event.

The earnings are partly donated to:
- #TezosStandsWithUkraine
- #Tezos4Iran

Made with love, AI and p5.js code

November, 2022
Julia V & YulikolaY
